    "content": "nullSalesforce B2B Commerce for Visualforce\nTABLE OF CONTENTS\nClose\nClose\nSearch\nSearch\n Salesforce B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Get Started with B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Manage Storefront Details and Metadata\n Set Up Product Data for B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Help Buyers Discover Products on Your Storefront\n Price and Sell Products for B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Support Buyer Accounts for B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Provide a Smooth Path to Purchase for Storefront Buyers\n Customize the Storefront User Experience\n Strategize for Storefront Success\n Internationalize Your Storefront\n Select Which Locales and Currencies Your Storefront Supports\n Translate Storefront Text for Buyers in Different Locales\n Add or Change the List of Available Languages, Locales, or Currencies\n Create a Price List for Each Supported Currency\n Update a Storefront User's Locale and Currency Settings\n Page Label Format for Currency Values\n Remove a Locale from a Storefront\n Boost Storefront Traffic with SEO\n Track Storefront Activity with Google Analytics 4\n Create a Portal to Your Storefront from an Experience Builder Site\n Create Associations between Multiple Storefronts and Experience...\n Show a Storefront at the Root of Your Domain\n Deliver Storefront Performance and Security\n Market Templates for B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n Solution Resources for B2B Commerce for Visualforce\n\nYou are here:\n\nSALESFORCE HELP\nDOCS\nVISUALFORCE B2B COMMERCE\nPage Label Format for Currency Values\n\nTo show prices on your storefront, create a page label record for each currency that your storefront supports. The value of the page label record specifies the symbol, delimiters, and decimal places to show for a particular currency.\n\nREQUIRED EDITIONS\n\nSalesforce Compatibility\n\nSalesforce Classic (not available in all orgs) and Lightning Experience for Enterprise, Performance, Unlimited, and Developer editions.\n\n\n\n\nB2B Commerce Compatibility\n\nB2B Commerce for Visualforce Winter ’21 (version 4.13)\nB2B Commerce for Visualforce Spring ’20 (version 4.12)\nB2B Commerce for Visualforce Summer ’19 (version 4.11)\nB2B Commerce for Visualforce Spring ’19 (version 4.10)\nB2B Commerce for Visualforce Summer ’18 (version 4.9)\nPage Label Name\n\nName each currency's page label record price_CUR, where CUR is the ISO 4217 currency code, such as USD or JPY. For example, the page label record for USD currency is named price_USD and the page label recod for JPY currency is price_JPY.\n\nPage Label Rich Text Value\n\nIn the ValueRT field of the page label record, specify the currency format, including the following details. For specific examples, see Currency Format Examples.\n\nNOTE When you create a value in a Lightning Experience Rich Text field, an extra <p> is inserted. Unless you intend to add data after the <p>, remove it. For more information about limitations with Rich Text fields, see Rich Text Area Field Limitations.\nPrefix\nCharacters that appear before the currency amount, such as the USD ($) sign or JPY (¥) sign.\n\nYou can specify any characters except:\n\nNumbers (0–9)\nThe number or hash sign (#)\nPlus (+) or minus (−) sign\nInteger\nThe whole number portion of the price. For example, in the price $19.85, the value 19 is the integer.\nUse the number or hash sign (#) as a placeholder for each digit to show.\nTo force a zero character to show for any particular digit, enter a 0.\nInclude the appropriate delimiter character, such as a comma (̦), to break up large integers. The delimiter pattern scales as the magnitude of the integer scales. For example, the integer pattern #,### shows the price 1234 as 1,234 and the price 1234567 as 1,234,567.\nDecimal\nThe fractional portion of the price. For example, in the price $19.85, the value .85 is the decimal.\nUse the number or hash sign (#) as a placeholder for each significant digit.\nInclude the appropriate delimiter character, such as a period (.), to separate the integer from the decimal.\nTo omit the decimal portion entirely, enter only a delimiter character for the decimal. If the price includes a decimal value, the currency price shown on the storefront rounds up to the nearest integer.\nSuffix\nCharacters that appear at the end of the currency format, such as the EUR (€) sign.\n\nYou can specify any characters except:\n\nNumbers (0–9)\nThe number or hash sign (#)\nPlus (+) or minus (−) sign\nCurrency Format Examples\nPAGE LABEL VALUE\tPRICE\tCURRENCY SHOWN ON THE STOREFRONT\n#,###.##\t1234.56\t1,234.56\n1234567.89\t1,234,567.89\n0.01\t.01\n0.011\t.01\n0.016\t.02\n#,##0.##\t0.01\t0.01\n$#,###.##\t1234.56\t$1,234.56\n#,###.## USD\t1234.56\t1,234.56 USD\n####.\t123456\t123456\n123456.78\t123457\n####.00\t123456.1\t123456.10\n#,###.00 €\t123456789.0\t123,456,789.00 €\n# ## ##\t1234.56\t12 34 56\nSEE ALSO\nCustomize Storefront Headings and Text with Page Labels\nDID THIS ARTICLE SOLVE YOUR ISSUE?\nLet us know so we can improve!\nYes\nNo\n ",
